args: Yes, I should be able to cook all\nmanner of dishes with these utensils.
And with this light, breathable outfit\non my back, I am ready to set out!
Goodness, Cleo. Where are you off to\nwith all of this gear?
Oh, just a little mountain camping trip.
Aside from the fact you are not known\nto enjoy climbing mountains in the\nslightest, you mean?
True, it's not my favorite activity...
But it'll be worth it for all of the wonderful\nnew foods I will be able to gather!
Yes, but it's a FIEND rice ball!\nMitsuba and I made them.
Yep! We really just want you to be able\nto join our little fiendmeat party.
When you share delicious food with\neveryone, it only makes it better!
I had been avoiding fiend cuisine due to\nits appearance—as well as my own\nprejudices on the subject.
But thanks to Pecorine, I learned not\nto judge things before I can try them.
Now I suspect there to be an entire world\nof things I've long assumed inedible that\nare actually quite tasty.
When I think about that,\nI can scarce sit still.
Which explains the camping trip.\nSpeaking of which, might I come with?
If anything unforeseen should happen,\ntwo can handle it better than one.
I would be glad for the company!
We've hiked quite a ways today.\nShall we take a break?
You're practically out of breath, Cleo—\nand no wonder when your pack weighs\nmore than a dragon! We're stopping.
Please, let's just climb a little higher.\nI hear the foraging is better the closer\none gets to the top of the mountain.
You are a woman possessed\nwhen food is involved...
Are you sure you're well, Cleo?\nYou look rather unsteady.
*sputter* I'm fine! Stronger than ever\nin fac—WHOOOOA!
Don't let go! I'll pull you up! Nnnngh...\nBlast! You're slipping!
Elisanne, wait! I'll unhook my pack!
I'm sorry I couldn't lift both you\nand your possessions, Cleo.
Say no more about it. If I'd not let my pack\ngo, I would be splattered at the bottom of\nthe cliff along with my possessions.
I'm simply grateful you helped me.
Your pack WAS incredibly heavy.\nWhat exactly was in it, anyway?
Let me think... Four portable cooking pots,\ntwo cast-iron skillets, a knife, charcoal,\na cutting board, cooking oil—

I wanted to be able to cook up whatever
I found right where I found it—though
perhaps I was overthinking the issue,
now that I look back on it.
I'm impressed you made it this far with\nsuch immense weight on your back.
I know you're passionate about cooking,\nbut that is a mad amount of equipment\nto haul up a mountai—*gurgle*
Goodness! I fear all this talk of cooking\nhas my stomach rumbling.
Mine seems to be doing the same.\nI wonder if there is anything we can\nmake around here.
Did we not just lose all of our cookware?
Oh, I'm certain I'll think of something.\nFirst, let's see what we can forage!
I was able to find a few varieties of nuts\nand mushrooms, as well as wild greens.
All edible, but certainly not easy to eat\nin their current state.
The wild greens especially will be quite\nbitter if we don't cook them first.
And yet, as we have established,\nour cookware is at the bottom of a cliff.
Perhaps we could heat up a flat rock\nand use it as a frying pan.
A fine idea! Let us find a suitable stone\nand see if the plan bears fruit.
Putting a flat rock on top of a campfire\nto cook food was a good idea, but...
But the food is stuck to the rock\nand burning. Badly, I might add.
Elisanne, where are the nuts you found?
I set them aside after I tried to eat one\nand nearly cracked a tooth in two.
They might be too hard for eating,\nbut we can still use them for oil!
If we crush them with this rock...\nYes, look! Oil! Quickly, pour that on\nthe flat rock that is our frying pan!
Now our food won't stick.\nLet's try this again...
It looks and smells fantastic, Cleo.\nI cannot wait to try it.
*chomp* Oh, but this is divine...\nAnd to think we made it from items\nwe foraged from the mountainside!
I'm glad you like it, though I'm sorry I\ncouldn't make anything more extravagant.
I should have listened to you and taken\na break. If I had, we'd still have all my\ncookware and ingredients.
Don't worry about that, Cleo. In fact, the\nexperience taught me a valuable lesson.
You told me there was a world of things\nyou'd assumed were inedible that could\nactually be quite tasty, remember?
Well, I'm impressed by your innovation.\nTake the nuts, for example. Not only did\nthe oil do its job, it was delicious as well!
I would have just given up on them,\nfiguring they were inedible.
What, that? I just happened to know that\nsimilar nuts could be used in such a way.
And your knowledge has left me\nwith a very full stomach.
Also, I haven't even mentioned your idea\nto use a flat rock as a frying pan.
I'm confident you could whip up a\nfine meal in ANY situation!
But who knows what the future holds?\nBeing able to cook well in the wild\nmight prove a handy skill indeed.
At least we know we won't go hungry.
And perhaps I can get even better\nat campfire cooking!
